A vs B

Tools are used to sample different concntrations of seeded virus. A recovered from -1 inoculated coupon area. B recovered from -3 inoculated coupon area.

data%>% 
  filter(Tool%in% c("A", "B"))%>%
  count(Method)
##   Method   n
## 1    CDC  70
## 2    NTP 216
AsksP2P1<-data%>% 
  filter(Tool%in% c("A", "B"), Input!="6400")%>%
  ggplot(aes(x=Tool, y= Ct))+
  geom_boxplot(aes(color=Method))+
  geom_hline(yintercept=27, linetype="longdash", color = "orange")+ #CDC confirmed threshold
  geom_hline(yintercept=37, linetype="longdash", color = "blue")+ #General confirmed threshold
  facet_grid(Detector~Input)+
  scale_y_reverse()+
  labs(y="Ct Value",
       x=NULL,
       title="Phase 2 Comparing A and B tool recovery")

print(AsksP2P1)
## Warning: Removed 19 rows containing non-finite values (stat_boxplot).

#save figure
figure_file = here("results","ASK-P2P1-Tools.png")
ggsave(filename = figure_file, plot=AsksP2P1) 
## Saving 7 x 5 in image
## Warning: Removed 19 rows containing non-finite values (stat_boxplot).

Tool A has an average Ct recovery higher than B. This makes sense as the surfaces A recovered from is 2 logs higher (-1) than that of B (-3). A log drop is ~3Ct values we can see from the graphic that it trends as predicted. Suggests that

CDC vs NTP

Compare the different extraction methods Serial Dilutions

AsksP2P2<-data%>%
  mutate(Dilution=as.numeric(as.factor(Dilution)))%>%
  filter(Tool=="SD", Input=="300")%>%
  ggplot(aes(x=Dilution, y=Ct, color=Method))+
  scale_y_reverse()+
  geom_point()+
  geom_smooth(aes(fill=Method),method=lm, alpha=0.20, fullrange=TRUE)+
  geom_hline(yintercept=27, linetype="longdash", color = "orange")+ #CDC confirmed threshold
#  geom_hline(yintercept=37, linetype="longdash", color = "blue")+ #General confirmed threshold
  facet_wrap(Detector~Tool)+
  labs(title = "Serial Dilution comparisons between CDC and NTP Methods, Input at 300.")

print(AsksP2P2)

Serial dilution data between CDC and NTP. Noting that all SD are in the confirmed realm of under 27 Ct Value CDC method is better than NTP at -1 concentration of the SD. the -2 shows little difference between method recovery Ct values. NTP appears to remain better than CDC at -3 and -4 levels. Accounting for the SE looks like both methods are the same until the -2 dilution. Might be significant difference at the -4 dilution.

Compare between extraction methods at input 300

NTP Input variations

Serial Dilution

AsksP2P5<-data%>%
  mutate(Dilution=as.numeric(as.factor(Dilution)))%>%
  filter(Method=="NTP", Tool=="SD", Input!="CTRL", Input!="6800")%>%
  ggplot(aes(x=Dilution, y=Ct, color=Input))+
  scale_y_reverse()+
  geom_jitter()+
  geom_smooth(method=lm, se=FALSE, fullrange=TRUE)+
  geom_hline(yintercept=27, linetype="longdash", color = "orange")+ #CDC confirmed threshold
  facet_wrap(.~Detector)+
  labs(title="Comparing Input levels on the Serial Dilituions with for the NTP method.")

print(AsksP2P5)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

## Warning: Removed 3 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

NTP SD is similar to CDC SD in that the Ct values remain under 27, the most confirmed presence of nCoV-2. Interesting! Looks like 300 input is really the lowest and as the inputs increase they kind of converge together at the -3 dilution level. Interpretation: better detection at high copy levels with lower input; better detection at low copy levels with more input;

If we could determine how many copies are in the -3 dilution we may be able to better estimate the capacity of the particles.

NTP

AsksP2P6<-data%>%
  mutate(Dilution=as.numeric(as.factor(Dilution)))%>%
  filter(Method=="NTP", Input=="300"|Input=="1000")%>%
